NAME: No Semantics
COMMENT: No further semantics is given, why the information is missing

NAME: Not Encoded
COMMENT: The actual value has not yet been encoded within the approved value domain.

NAME: Unknown
COMMENT: A proper value is applicable, but not known. This is typically the case, if there are artefacts (tissue folds or overlap, etc.) which do not allow a classification

NAME: No proper Value
COMMENT: Known to have no proper value, this will be the most common null value e.g. when there is no tissue.

NAME: Epithelial tissue
COMMENT: This tissue covers the entire body and all internal hollow organs. It serves as a protective layer and is also involved in the secretion and absorption processes.

NAME: Muscle tissue
COMMENT: This tissue allows movement and is divided into three main types

NAME: Muscle Skeletal
COMMENT: Skeletal muscle tissue: Allows voluntary movement and support

NAME: Muscle Smooth
COMMENT: Provides involuntary movement of internal organs such as the stomach or intestines

NAME: Muscle Cardiac
COMMENT: Cardiac muscle tissue (cardiomyocytes): Responsible for the contraction of the heart

NAME: Nervous tissue
COMMENT: This tissue consists of neurons and glial cells that transmit and process information to coordinate all the body's functions.

NAME: Conective Tissue
COMMENT: Connective tissue: This very diverse tissue provides structure and support for other tissues and organs

NAME: Conective Tissue Loose
COMMENT: Loose connective tissue: Fills spaces between organs and supports epithelium and many internal organs

NAME: Conective Tissue Dense
COMMENT: Dense connective tissue: Contains tendons and ligaments

NAME: Conective Tissue Fat
COMMENT: Fatty tissue: Stores energy and serves as padding

NAME: Conective Tissue Cartilage
COMMENT: Provides structural components for many organs (e.g. nose, ears, joints)
